:\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Refining test coverage**\\\\n\\\\nI’m thinking about refining the test to ensure that line 62 is counted as covered, even if exceptions occur. It seems unnecessary to complicate things further. The user reported an error, and we fixed it, but now they've provided an update on their role task progress, indicating that attempts have been used.\\\\n\\\\nI’m considering splitting the tests to improve this process. Maybe we should update the test to check for line 62 failures through a helper, which might be sufficient. I also need to ensure that it correctly logs dynamic access calls and that we’re accounting for JDK versions properly.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering tests and classloaders**\\\\n\\\\nI’m thinking about adding a test that calls the API in a new isolated classloader. This could prevent any poisoning of JvmUtils from prior tests. Since if the initializer fails once, subsequent references won't cover line 62 in the current setup, which only allows one attempt per test.\\\\n\\\\nIf I add another test method, it risks JvmUtils causing a NoClassDefFoundError after the first catch. So, I need to find a way to avoid that. Using separate forks per test or JUnit's `@TestMethodOrder` doesn't seem like the right solution either.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_RdvoIfj5hNK6wsEbBs9c0e4y|fc_0b9534823d32c12b016a0239206b60819da4d2ab67c5c9f42d\", \"name\": \"read\", \"arguments\": {\"path\": \"tests/src/software.amazon.eventstream/eventstream/1.0.1/src/test/java/software_amazon_eventstream/eventstream/EventstreamTest.java\", \"limit\": 30}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 1703, \"output\": 1265, \"cacheRead\": 41472, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 44440, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1778530571627, \"responseId\": \"resp_0b9534823d32c12b016a02390d059c819d82a6a025b1eb216c\"}}\nhuman-intervention-logs/io.airlift:slice:0.36/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-11T20-05-14-042553Z.log:3359:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Refining test coverage**\\n\\nI’m thinking about refining the test to ensure that line 62 is counted as covered, even if exceptions occur. It seems unnecessary to complicate things further. The user reported an error, and we fixed it, but now they've provided an update on their role task progress, indicating that attempts have been used.\\n\\nI’m considering splitting the tests to improve this process. Maybe we should update the test to check for line 62 failures through a helper, which might be sufficient. I also need to ensure that it correctly logs dynamic access calls and that we’re accounting for JDK versions properly.\\n\\n**Considering tests and classloaders**\\n\\nI’m thinking about adding a test that calls the API in a new isolated classloader. This could prevent any poisoning of JvmUtils from prior tests. Since if the initializer fails once, subsequent references won't cover line 62 in the current setup, which only allows one attempt per test.\\n\\nIf I add another test method, it risks JvmUtils causing a NoClassDefFoundError after the first catch. So, I need to find a way to avoid that. Using separate forks per test or JUnit's `@TestMethodOrder` doesn't seem like the right solution either.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_0b9534823d32c12b016a02390db5c8819da3be43c6f31ddf83\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABqAjkg4qKLTsH3hPMpMEokjrHpKIEjIziyEFPr9u4d5jswwEhD64fQpeLjB3K7tmLrizCWjH7e-UGBPdq5NjrkVzYEIPyyNXHLxDEUxeZgFaswKdoJBb2_QU7pbjehqOuUYBrTVQVPy8tS5jEvkHmPFMHAE-TWVQX5l6MxGBDSQBBKlU1oP22GrkRMCx-n423OgXMpTf_AEPrQm_ffXNtwpkoEmbXKKLLM3A11V1I-oznICZKvE-W2xq1HgpUzehF2EUj7cxuyNBZ-RrglhfdeU